Synopsis:

    This application will display and play the JR-Yamanote Line station 
    names and jingles in real-time via an arduino with a connected speaker.

ATTENTION!!:

    If you want to implement this project for yourself you will need to sign
    up to the ODPT website here: 
    https://www.odpt.org/en/
    
    This will give you access to the API to begin recieving the train data.
    You will not be able to make this project work without the access key.
    Further, you will need to sign up to the challenge in order to query the
    JR-Line.

Inspiration:

    Born out of my recent visit to Japan; I grew accustomed to hearing the
    various station jingles that signaled my arrival at a particular station.
    Each jingle was unique and a beautiful way of indicating to passangers that
    they arrived. This project seeks to ecapsulate that same feeling but from
    affar by utilizing Japan's own live train data to track a train and play
    a particular station jingle for whichever station the train arrives at.

Operation:

    For now the application simply queries the JR-Line (the one I used most
    and which in particular has the best station jingle; Ikebukuro's BIC Camera 
    jingle) but I plan to add functionality that will allow a user to select a
    particular operator should they so choose. Please stay tuned for when I update
    it with that functionality.

    For this application, I wrote a StringBuffer object as the ardunio IDE does not
    natively support it. It is not strictly necessary; through my testing, creating
    a dedicated char array in each read response works just as well. Having the
    StringBuffer gives me more peace of mind though. If you want to use the object
    simply add the .hpp & .cpp files to the arduino IDE library folder explained 
    here: 
    
    https://docs.arduino.cc/learn/contributions/arduino-creating-library-guide/

    The Stringbuffer code can be found here:

    https://github.com/Joshm0/Arduino-Stringbuffer

    This way, if you want to use the library for any of your other projects (:D) you 
    can simply import it the way you would for any normal library!

    This code is free to use, all I ask is you provide a link to this github page
    and credit the original code.

